This is a great car from a Northern CA estate collection a few months ago. This car is BEAST. Runs amazing with a fresh big block 454 tied to what is believed to be 400 auto tranny with a fuel cell in the trunk, headers & new dual exhaust. It has a few little issues like a 54 yr old car will...but it's a blast to drive. It's missing one small piece of trim on the passenger front fender. Other than that it has all chrome and trim in great shape (try looking up the value of the trim & bumpers). All windows, doors, trunk, & hood close properly & solidly. All lines are straight and true. It runs, turns and stops just fine althought the brakes need adjustment bc it pulls to left when theyre applied. Interior upholstry & headliner look great. Dash could use a little love but very presentable. It has some rust issues underneath that I discovered when I got the car but that didnt bother me. Paint is an amatuer "10 footer" with great flake. title: For Sale:  (   )Remington No. 1 Argentino Rolling Block
postcontent:
REMINGTON SINGLE SHOT MILITARY NUMBER 1 ROLLING BLOCK RIFLE USED AS THE CHIEF SERVICE ARM OF MANY ARMIES IN THE SECOND HALF OF THE 19TH CENTURY. This is a .43 SPANISH (11.15X58MMR) caliber. ANTIQUE  NO FFL TRANSFER REQUIRED. 

Probably over one million Remington Number 1 size rolling block rifles were made between 1867 and 1888. They were purchased in large quantities and in many different calibers and configurations by many countries including Argentina, Norway, Denmark, Spain, Turkey, Egypt and Mexico. Barrel lengths and other specifications differed from country to country. They were hard used for long periods of time and fought in many different wars. It was used by either the Spanish or Argentine military. The barrel and receiver both have a few areas of pitting in the metal. The barrel is 35 inches long and has an excellent bore with great rifling and no pitting. There are the usual slight dings and dents but no heavy gouging. The gun has it's cleaning rod. The rifle still functions perfectly. The multi line Remington roll stamp of name and patent dates is on the top tang and is still readable. Not the prettiest rifle Ive ever sold, but its got tons of character and is a great example of 19th Century military history. Antique  No FFL or C&R required  can be shipped right to your door. Like I said before this is not a wall hanger. It has a bright and shiny bore with pronounced rifling. I am including a box of 20 rounds of Ammo, also. Yes Buffalo arms black powder 370 grn, ammo. Perfect for those montana buffalo poaching trips on Ted's private prarie, lol. Keep your brass and you can be reloading with a $50.00 set of dies. Much funner than percussion, lol.

Sorry, I don't have the original box and papers. Gun is in good fireable shape. It has been in the safe for many years only to be pulled and cleaned and inspected. Look at my other ads also. I will be selling the bulk of my collection over the next month or so to fund a large project. I will have some things for sale that will interest all different collectors and shooters.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Chinese Norinco SKS. All matching. A true beauty.
postcontent:
All matching Norinco Chinese sks. Sporter version. Non thumbhole stock and does not accept ak mags. Is 100% matching, original and real. Have green sling, cleaning kit that fits in stock, screwdriver type bayonet. Comes with a 30 rnd deatatcheable polymer Tapco mag and 860 rounds of various factory ammo (norinco steel core, Winchester, brown bear, golden bear, silver bear, Tula and wolf). I have owned for over 22 years. Less than 500 rounds shot thru it. Well taken care of and pristine condition. Again all numbers match. Is stamped Tucson AZ. Is also a legit DB stamp.  Here's the history:

In 1989 sks were stamped sporter or sks-m to be allowed for import after a 1989 ban. These rifles were fitted with Monte Carlo or thumbhole stocks. Also made and adapted to accept ak mags. Also had the bayo lug removed. The rifle I have has had none of the cosmetic changes yet is stamped sporter. Plus it has the DB stamp. That means deport Bangladesh. Some Chinese made sks were stamped this or DP(Pakistan) or DK(Kampuchea). DP typically adds 10% value. DK about 15-20%. And the most rare DB adding up to 50% based on condition. Many DP have been forged to appear DB. They are easy to tell due to the mis proportion of the humps of the B. so the sporter mis-stamp, DB stamp and #'s matching drives it to a collectors rifle. 
And when I mention the 1989 ban I don't mean the 1994 awb. The 1989 ban also ban import of norinco ammo which some is included with the rifle. A 20 rnd box of norinco was fetching 35-40 bucks before the paranoia after conn.
Also another change was the bolt carrier was changed on sporters with no slots for striped clips since they used ak removable mags and no stripper clip was needed. 
Most sporters had barrels shortened too.

Can sell minus ammo and Tapco mag for $900.
